<h1>Hotel Rooms</h1>

<p><a href="<?php echo $this->url('room/create'); ?>" style="background:#2c7a2c;color:#fff;padding:6px 14px;border-radius:4px;text-decoration:none;">+ Add Room</a></p>

<p>This page lists all rooms. It demonstrates <strong>ViewModel</strong> (passing data to the template)
and <strong>URL generation</strong> with <code>$this-&gt;url()</code>.</p>

<table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0;">
    <thead>
        <tr style="background: #2c7a2c; color: #fff;">
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Room #</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Type</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: right;">Price/Night</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Actions</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <?php foreach ($this->rooms as $room): ?>
        <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">
            <td style="padding: 10px;"><?php echo $this->escapeHtml($room['number']); ?></td>
            <td style="padding: 10px;"><?php echo $this->escapeHtml($room['type']); ?></td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: right;"><?php echo $room['price']; ?> BGN</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px;">
                <!-- url()->fromRoute() generates URLs from route names -->
                <a href="<?php echo $this->url('room/detail', array('id' => $room['id'])); ?>">Details</a>
            </td>
        </tr>
        <?php endforeach; ?>
    </tbody>
</table>

<p style="color: #666; font-size: 0.9em;">
    <strong>How the links work:</strong> Each "Details" link uses
    <code>$this-&gt;url('room/detail', array('id' =&gt; $room['id']))</code>
    to generate the URL. ZF2 builds the URL from the route configuration — you never hardcode URLs!
</p>
